Sedimentary Rock Formation Processes

1. Weathering

  • Definition:
    Breakdown of pre-existing rocks into smaller particles through physical, chemical, or biological processes.

  • Contribution to Sediments:

    • Physical weathering (mechanical breakdown) increases sediment supply.
    • Chemical weathering dissolves minerals, forming dissolved ions that can later precipitate.

2. Erosion

  • Definition:
    The removal and movement of weathered material from its source.

  • Agents of Erosion:

    • Wind
    • Water
    • Ice
    • Gravity

  • Significance:
    Erosion exposes fresh rock surfaces to further weathering.

3. Transportation

  • Definition:
    The movement of sediments from one location to another.

  • Transport Mechanisms:

    • Wind (e.g., desert dunes)
    • Running water (e.g., rivers transporting sand and silt)
    • Glaciers (e.g., moving large boulders and sediments)

  • Impact:

    • Determines the shape, size, and sorting of sediments.
    • Rounds sediments due to abrasion.

4. Deposition

  • Definition:
    The process where transported sediments settle or accumulate.

  • Triggers for Deposition:

    • Reduction in transport energy (e.g., river slows down)
    • Changes in water or air velocity

  • Examples:

    • River deltas
    • Sand dunes
    • Glacier deposits

How Deposition Occurs

  • When energy of transport medium decreases, sediments settle.
  • Examples:
    • Rivers slowing down â Deposits sediments in deltas.
    • Wind dying down â Forms sand dunes.

Chemical Deposition (Precipitation)

  • Definition:
    Dissolved materials precipitate and form solid minerals due to changes in temperature, pressure, or chemical composition.

  • Examples:

    • Evaporation of seawater â Formation of salt crystals.
    • Limestone formation from dissolved calcium carbonate.

5. Compaction

  • Definition:
    The process where sediment layers accumulate and compress due to overlying pressure.

  • Effect:

    • Reduces pore space between grains.
    • Expels water from sediments.

  • Example:

    • Mud transforming into shale.

6. Cementation

  • Definition:
    The binding of sediment particles by minerals precipitated from groundwater.

  • Common Cementing Agents:

    • Silica
    • Calcium carbonate
    • Iron oxides

  • Result:

    • Formation of solid sedimentary rock (e.g., sandstone, limestone).

Formation Processes

Source: Steven, E. (2015)

Classification of Sedimentary Rocks

Sedimentary rocks are classified into three main types based on their origin:

  1. Clastic Sedimentary Rocks (formed from rock fragments)
  2. Chemical Sedimentary Rocks (formed from mineral precipitation)
  3. Organic Sedimentary Rocks (formed from biological material)

Each type forms through different geological processes.

1. Clastic Sedimentary Rocks

Definition

  • Formed from mechanically weathered and transported rock fragments.
  • Classified based on sediment grain size.

Grain Size and Resulting Rocks

Sediment Size Rock Type Example
> 2 mm Conglomerate (rounded) / Breccia (angular) River gravel deposits
0.06 â 2 mm Sandstone Beach, desert dunes
0.002 â 0.06 mm Siltstone River floodplains
< 0.002 mm Shale / Mudstone Deep marine, lake deposits
  • Sorting & Rounding:
    • Well-sorted: Long transport distance (e.g., beach sand).
    • Poorly sorted: Short transport distance (e.g., glacial deposits).

2. Chemical Sedimentary Rocks

Definition

  • Formed when minerals precipitate from solution due to changes in temperature, pressure, or water chemistry.
  • Typically found in evaporite deposits, caves, and ocean basins.

3. Organic Sedimentary Rocks

Definition

  • Formed from accumulation of organic material (plants, shells, or microscopic organisms).
  • Typically associated with swamps, marine environments, and coral reefs.

Examples of Organic Rocks

Rock Type Composition Formation Environment Example
Coal Carbon from compressed plant material Swamps Peat, bituminous coal

    • Example: Coral reefs and shell deposits forming limestone.

Rock Type Description & Characteristics Example Locations
